Name: Root-Mean-Square Energy (mean)
Description: The root mean square energy calculates the global energy of the signal. It is computed by taking the root average of the square of the amplitude, also called root-mean-square (RMS). Roughly describes the loudness of a musical signal.

Name: Low Energy Rate
Description: The low energy rate measures the percentage of frames showing less-than-average energy (Tzanetakis and Cook, 2002). The energy curve can be used to get an assessment of the temporal distribution of energy, in order to see if its remains constant throughout the signal, or if some frames are more contrastive than others.

Name: Average Silence Ratio
Description: The original source proposes this feature as na estimation for Articulation. The Average Silence Ratio (Feng, Zhuang, Pan, 2003), is available in MIR Toolbox under mirlowenergy function and corresponds to a RMS without the square-root, and a default threshold set to t = .5.

Name: Fluctuation (mean)
Description: Rhythmic Periodicity along Auditory Channels. This feature estimates the rhythm content based on spectrogram computation transformed by auditory modelling and then a spectrum estimation in each band (Pampalk et al., 2002).

Name: Fluctuation (std)
Description: Rhythmic Periodicity along Auditory Channels. This feature estimates the rhythm content based on spectrogram computation transformed by auditory modelling and then a spectrum estimation in each band (Pampalk et al., 2002).

Name: Beat Spectrum (mean)
Description: The beat spectrum has been proposed as a measure of acoustic self-similarity as a function of time lag, and is computed from the similarity matrix (using Frame Similarity Matrix: mirsimatrix) (Foote, Cooper and Nam, 2002).

Name: Beat Spectrum (std)
Description: The beat spectrum has been proposed as a measure of acoustic self-similarity as a function of time lag, and is computed from the similarity matrix (using Frame Similarity Matrix: mirsimatrix) (Foote, Cooper and Nam, 2002).

Name: Events Density
Description: Estimates the average frequency of events, i.e., the number of note onsets per second.

Name: Tempo (Classical)
Description: Estimates the tempo by detecting periodicities from the onset detection curve. According to the manual, the classical paradigm for tempo estimation is based on detecting periodicities in a range of BPMs, and choosing the maximum periodicity score for each frame separately. The classical method generates a tempo curve with a lot of shifts from one metrical level to another.

Name: Tempo (Metre) (mean)
Description: Estimates the tempo by detecting periodicities from the onset detection curve. The metre-based version tracks tempo by building a hierarchical metrical structure (using mirmetre). This enables to find coherent metrical levels leading to a continuous tempo curve.

Name: Tempo Change (mean)
Description: The difference between successive values of the tempo curve. Tempo change is expressed independently from the choice of a metrical level by computing the ratio of tempo values between successive frames, and is expressed in logarithmic scale (base 2), so that no tempo change gives a value of 0, increase of tempo gives positive value, and decrease of tempo gives negative value.

Name: Metrical Centroid and Strength (mean)
Description: Dynamic metrical centroid: an assessment of metrical activity that is based on the computation of the centroid of the selected metrical levels. Dynamic metrical strength: indicates whether there is a clear and strong pulsation, or even a strong metrical hierarchy, or whether on in the other hand the pulsation is somewhat hidden, unclear, or there is a complex mixture of pulsations.

Name: Rolloff (mean)
Description: The amount of high frequency in the signal. Consists in finding the frequency such that a certain fraction of the total energy is contained below that frequency. In MIR Toolbox, this ratio is fixed by default to 0.85.

Name: High-frequency Energy (mean)
Description: Another metric of High-frequency Energy also known as Brightness. Consists in fixing the cut-off frequency, and measuring the amount of energy above that frequency (Juslin, 2000). The result is expressed as a number between 0 and 1.

Name: Spectral Flux (mean)
Description: Spectral flux is a measure of how quickly the power spectrum of a signal is changing, calculated by comparing (the difference) the power spectrum for one frame against the power spectrum from the previous frame.

Name: Spectral Skewness (mean)
Description: Coefficient of skewness. The third central moment is called the skewness and is a measure of the symmetry of the distribution. A positive coefficient of skewness often indicates that the distribution exhibits a concentration of mass toward the left and a long tail to the right whereas a negative value generally indicates the opposite.

A positive coefficient of skewness often indicates that the distribution exhibits a concentration of mass toward the left and a long tail to the right whereas a negative value generally indicates the opposite.
